Three possible ways to combine encryption and MACs are:

- Encrypt first, apply the MAC to the ciphertext (Encrypt-then-MAC);
- Apply the MAC first, encrypt plaintext and MAC together (MAC-then-Encrypt);
- Apply the MAC and encrypt the plaintext separately (Encrypt-and-MAC).

Which is used in the TLS Record Protocol (up to version 1.2) and which in the ESP protocol of IPsec? Why is the third option not suitable in general?

The messaging protocol Signal uses pre-computed Diffie-Hellman keys to protect the first message in any conversation. Client $A$ pre-computes many $t_i = g^{x_i}$ values stored on the Signal server. When client $B$ starts a new conversation with $A$:

- $B$ receives an unused pre-computed key $t_i = g^{x_i}$, which is then deleted from the server;
- $B$ chooses an ephemeral DH private key $x_B$;
- $B$ computes a message key $k$ as a hash of $g^{x_i x_B}$;
- $B$ sends the first message protected by $k$ and also sends $g^{x_B}$;
- $A$ receives the message, uses $x_i$ to recompute $k$, recovers the message, and deletes $x_i$;
- For the next message, $A$ computes a new ephemeral DH value combined with $g^{x_B}$ for the next key.

Signal has a fallback mechanism to reuse the last available pre-computed key for many conversations until replenished (suggested weekly or monthly).

Discuss how this process influences forward secrecy for the first message. Should pre-computed values be classed as long-term or ephemeral keys?
